</a></div>

<div style=3D"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;=
"><strong><a href=3D"https://library.soton.ac.uk/variance-standard-deviatio=
n-and-standard-error#Main%20heading%201">Variance</a></strong></div>

<div style=3D"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;=
"><strong><a href=3D"https://library.soton.ac.uk/variance-standard-deviatio=
n-and-standard-error#Main%20heading%202">Standard Deviation</a></strong></d=
iv>

<div style=3D"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;=
"><strong><a href=3D"https://library.soton.ac.uk/variance-standard-deviatio=
n-and-standard-error#Main%20heading%203">Standard Error</a></strong></div>

<div style=3D"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;=
"><a href=3D"https://library.soton.ac.uk/variance-standard-deviation-and-st=
andard-error#Examples"><strong>Examples&nbsp;</strong></a></div>

<div style=3D"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;=
"><a href=3D"https://library.soton.ac.uk/variance-standard-deviation-and-st=
andard-error#Video:%20standard%20deviation%20vs.%20standard%20error"><b>Vid=
eo: Standard Deviation vs. Standard Error</b></a></div>

<hr>
<h3><strong><a id=3D"Annotated Bibliography - Fast facts" name=3D"Annotated=
 Bibliography - Fast facts">Fast facts</a></strong></h3>

<ul>
	<li>Both variance and standard deviation are measures of spread.</li>
	<li>Standard deviation is equal to the square root of the variance.</li>
	<li>Standard deviation is used to describe the data, and standard error is=
 used to describe&nbsp;statistical accuracy.</li>
	<li>It is easier to calculate these using software than by hand.</li>
</ul>

<hr>
<h3><strong><a id=3D"Main heading 1" name=3D"Main heading 1">Variance</a></=
strong></h3>

<p>Variance is a measure of how far the observed values in a dataset fall f=
rom the arithmetic&nbsp;mean, and is therefore a measure of spread - more s=
pecifically, it is a measure of variability. It is denoted by the Greek let=
ter sigma squared, and its formula is given by:</p>

<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><img alt=3D"sigma squared equals the sum o=
f x minus x bar squared all divided by n which is also equal to the sum of =
x squared divided by n minus x bar squared" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https:/=
/libapps-eu.s3.amazonaws.com/accounts/1311/images/Variance_formula.png"></p=
>

<p>where:</p>

<ul>
	<li><em>=CF=83<sup>2</sup></em>&nbsp;is the variance we are wanting to fin=
d</li>
	<li><em><img alt=3D"\sum" data-lazy-src=3D"https://www.scribbr.com/wp-cont=
ent/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-31219809315a90b0c3f443d9a8e7f10a_l3.png" data-l=
l-status=3D"loaded" decoding=3D"async" height=3D"19" loading=3D"lazy" src=
=3D"https://www.scribbr.com/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-31219809315a=
90b0c3f443d9a8e7f10a_l3.png" title=3D"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com" width=3D"=
18"></em>&nbsp;is the summation function</li>
	<li><em>x</em>&nbsp;is an observation in the dataset</li>
	<li><img alt=3D"x bar" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://libapps-eu.s3.amazo=
naws.com/accounts/1311/images/x_bar.png">is the population mean</li>
	<li><em>n</em>&nbsp;is the number of observations in the population.</li>
</ul>

<ul>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<hr>
<h3><span style=3D"font-size:22px;"></span><strong><a id=3D"Main heading 2"=
 name=3D"Main heading 2">Standard Deviation</a></strong></h3>

<p>Standard deviation is the square root of the variance, and therefore is =
also a&nbsp;measure of spread - more specifically, it is a measure of dispe=
rsion (or, the measure of variability!). Where variance is used to show how=
 much the values in a dataset vary from each other, the standard deviation =
exists to show how far apart the values in a dataset are from the mean, and=
 therefore can be used to identify outliers.</p>

<p>Standard deviation is denoted by the Greek letter sigma and, being the s=
quare root of variance, is written as:</p>

<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><img alt=3D"sigma equals the square root o=
f variance equals the square root of the sum of x minus x bar squared divid=
ed by n equals the square root of the sum of x squared divided by n minus x=
 bar sqaured" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://libapps-eu.s3.amazonaws.com/a=
ccounts/1311/images/Standard_Deviation_formula.png" style=3D"width: 336px; =
height: 90px;"></p>

<p>where:</p>

<ul>
	<li><em>=CF=83<sup>2</sup></em>&nbsp;is the variance we are wanting to fin=
d</li>
	<li><em><img alt=3D"\sum" data-lazy-src=3D"https://www.scribbr.com/wp-cont=
ent/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-31219809315a90b0c3f443d9a8e7f10a_l3.png" data-l=
l-status=3D"loaded" decoding=3D"async" height=3D"19" loading=3D"lazy" src=
=3D"https://www.scribbr.com/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-31219809315a=
90b0c3f443d9a8e7f10a_l3.png" title=3D"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com" width=3D"=
18"></em>&nbsp;is the summation function</li>
	<li><em>x</em>&nbsp;is an observation in the dataset</li>
	<li><img alt=3D"x bar" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://libapps-eu.s3.amazo=
naws.com/accounts/1311/images/x_bar.png">is the population mean</li>
	<li><em>n</em>&nbsp;is the number of observations in the population.</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<hr>
<h3><strong><a id=3D"Main heading 3" name=3D"Main heading 3">Standard Error=
</a></strong></h3>

<p>Standard error is another measure of spread. The most common standard er=
ror is the standard error of the mean, and used to measure sampling error a=
s it measures how accurately the mean of a&nbsp;sample distribution represe=
nts the mean of the population. In other words, it shows how much variation=
 there is likely to be between different samples of a&nbsp;population and t=
he population itself.</p>

<p>The main difference between the standard deviation and the standard erro=
r is that the standard deviation is a type of descriptive statistics, used =
to summarise the data, whereas the standard error of the mean describes the=
 random sampling process, and is an estimation rather than a definite value=
 like the standard deviation is. It&nbsp;is useful because you can see how =
well your sample data represents your population.</p>

<p>The formula is given by:</p>

<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><img alt=3D"S E is equal to sigma divided =
by the square root of n is equal to one over the sqaure root of n multiplie=
d by the square root of the sum of x minus x bar sqaured divided by n is eq=
ual to one over the sqaure root of n multiplied by the square root of the s=
um of x squared divided by n minus x bar squared" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"h=
ttps://libapps-eu.s3.amazonaws.com/accounts/163698/images/standard_error.pn=
g" style=3D"width: 323px; height: 80px;"></p>

<p>where:&nbsp;</p>

<ul>
	<li><em>SE</em> is the standard error&nbsp;</li>
	<li><em>=CF=83</em>&nbsp;is the standard deviation</li>
	<li><em>n&nbsp;</em>is&nbsp;the sample size.</li>
</ul>

<hr>
<h3><span style=3D"font-size:22px;"></span><a id=3D"Examples" name=3D"Examp=
les"><strong>Examples</strong></a></h3>

<h4>Example 1</h4>

<p>Let's say we have the following dataset:</p>

<p style=3D"text-align: center;">7, 12, 5, 18, 5, 9, 10, 9, 12, 8, 12, 16</=
p>

<p>In order to find the variance and standard deviation of this, we need to=
 first find the mean, which is:</p>

<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><img alt=3D"seven plus twelve plus five pl=
us eighteen plus five plus nine plus ten plus nine plus twelve plus eight p=
lus twelve plus sixteen all divided by twelve equals one hundred and twenty=
 three divided by twelve equals ten point two five" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D=
"https://libapps-eu.s3.amazonaws.com/accounts/1311/images/mean_example_calc=
ulation.png" style=3D"width: 411px; height: 50px;"></p>

<p>The variance of this dataset is then given by:</p>

<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><img alt=3D"" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"http=
s://libapps-eu.s3.amazonaws.com/accounts/1311/images/Variance_example.png" =
style=3D"width: 535px; height: 60px;"></p>

<p>to two decimal places.</p>

<p>Then, the standard deviation is:</p>

<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><img alt=3D"" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"http=
s://libapps-eu.s3.amazonaws.com/accounts/1311/images/standard_deviation_exa=
mple.png" style=3D"width: 583px; height: 80px;"></p>

<p>to two decimal places, and the standard error is given by:</p>

<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><img alt=3D"standard error equals three po=
int eight three divided by the square root of twelve equaling one point one=
 one" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://libapps-eu.s3.amazonaws.com/accounts/=
1311/images/standard_error_example.png" style=3D"width: 139px; height: 60px=
;"></p>

<p>to two decimal places.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h4>Example 2</h4>

<p>Calculating the variance and standard deviation by hand is a long-winded=
 process, and with large datasets there is much room for human error. Using=
 software for these sorts of calculations tends to be the more ideal thing =
to do.</p>

<ul>
	<li>To calculate the variance and standard deviation of the above dataset =
in R, we can create a variable for the data and then calculate the variance=
 and standard deviation&nbsp;with the var and sd&nbsp;functions respectivel=
y:</li>
</ul>

<p style=3D"margin-left: 40px;"><code>dataset &lt;- c(7, 12, 5, 18, 5, 9, 1=
0, 9, 12, 8, 12, 16)</code></p>

<p style=3D"margin-left: 40px;"><code>var(dataset)</code></p>

<p style=3D"margin-left: 40px;"><code>sd(dataset)</code></p>

<p style=3D"margin-left: 40px;">To find the standard error, you can define =
your own function to be simply the standard deviation divided by the square=
 root of n and apply that function to the dataset:</p>

<p style=3D"margin-left: 40px;"><code>standard.error &lt;- function(x) sd(x=
)/sqrt(length(x))</code></p>

<p style=3D"margin-left: 40px;"><code>standard.error(dataset)</code></p>

<ul>
	<li>To calculate the variance and standard deviation in Excel, you can use=
 the VAR.S and&nbsp;STDEV&nbsp;functions respectively since the dataset is =
all numeric. If the dataset is contained in the cells A1 to A12, then the f=
unction you would write would be:</li>
</ul>

<p style=3D"margin-left: 40px;"><code>=3DVAR.S(A1:A12)</code></p>

<p style=3D"margin-left: 40px;"><code>=3DSTDEV(A1:A12)</code></p>

<p style=3D"margin-left: 40px;">The standard error will need to be written =
out yourself, using the above STDEV function with the COUNT function to fin=
d&nbsp;<em>n</em>:</p>

<p style=3D"margin-left: 40px;"><code>=3DSTDEV(A1:A12)/SQRT(COUNT(A1:A12))<=
/code></p>

<hr>
